title: Facebook, Twitter Lock Trump Out Of His Social Media Accounts After Capitol Violence
text: Twitter Inc (NYSE: TWTR) and Facebook Inc (NASDAQ: FB) have blocked outgoing President Donald Trump's accounts temporarily after the violent storming of the U.S. Capitol. What Happened: Twitter's safety account tweeted Wednesday that in the view of the “unprecedented” and “violent” situation in Washington, D.C.

title: USTR slams India, Italy, Turkey on digital taxes but holds off on tariffs
text: Digital services taxes adopted by India, Italy and Turkey discriminate against U.S. companies and are inconsistent with international tax principles, the U.S. Trade Representative's office said on Wednesday, paving the way for potential retaliatory tariffs.

title: Investor Joe Lonsdale on how Georgia Senate runoff races could impact tech stocks
text: Joe Lonsdale, 8VC founding partner and Palantir co-founder, joined "Squawk Box" on Wednesday to discuss why some of the most popular stay-at-home stocks such as Peloton and Netflix that moved lower Wednesday morning and how much the Georgia Senate runoff races may be contributing to the market volatility.

title: Facebook (FB) Bans Political Ads Post Georgia Senate Runoffs
text: Facebook (FB) is set to reinforce political ad bans in Georgia post Senate runoffs after facing criticism over misinformation handling.

title: Facebook drops 'likes' button from public pages
text: Facebook Inc has dropped the "likes" button from its redesigned public pages used by artists, public figures and brands, the social media company said on Wednesday.

title: Here's why the Georgia election results are a 'clear negative' for big tech, according to Wedbush
text: The likely blue sweep of Georgia by Senate candidates Raphael Warnock and Jon Ossoff will have big implications for technology stocks, according to a note from Wedbush's Daniel Ives. "To be blunt, it's a clear negative for Big Tech as ultimately with a Senate now likely controlled by Democrats we would expect much more scrutiny and sharper teeth around FAANG names," Ives explained.

title: Big tech stocks tumble as Wall Street braces for Democratic Senate
text: Big tech stocks fell sharply Wednesday as Democratic gains in Georgia stoked fears that the feds could tighten regulations on the industry's dominant players. Futures contracts linked to the tech-heavy Nasdaq 100 index tumbled about 1.3 percent as of 8:12 a.m.
